Zero-mile rows are meaningful signal, not noise. The default
posture for a 0-mile entry is RULE OUT, not opt-in: a vehicle
that did not move CANNOT have driven to a merchant. The exception
requires explicit notes that say the service came to the vehicle.

  1. 0 mi + EXPLICIT notes that the service came to the vehicle
     (e.g. "Filled up with gas from gas can", "Mobile mechanic
     came out", "Oil change in the driveway", "New tires
     installed in garage"): the vehicle was stationary AND the
     purchase reached it where it sat. For fuel/maintenance/parts
     txns, this vehicle becomes a candidate. Without these
     notes, this case does NOT apply — fall through to case 2.

  2. 0 mi + NO notes (or notes that don't claim a come-to-vehicle
     service): "vehicle sat still today" marker. RULE OUT this
     vehicle for any txn whose service requires the vehicle to be
     physically AT the merchant: car wash, drive-through food,
     fuel pumped at a gas station, parking, drive-up tolls,
     restaurants, grocery store runs, errand-shaped purchases.
     A carwash specifically requires the car to arrive — 0 miles
     means it didn't, so the vehicle is NOT the attribution
     target. Pick a different vehicle (one that has miles logged
     for that date) or attribute the txn to a non-vehicle
     account.

  3. Cross-referenced notes between vehicles ("Went to gas station
     to get gas for <OtherVehicle>", "Filled up with gas from gas
     can"): the vehicle that DROVE is not necessarily the vehicle
     the purchase is attributed to. Follow the note's stated
     attribution target. The driving vehicle's fuel economy +
     miles still justifies its own (trivial) fuel-consumed share
     for that trip, but the txn itself attributes to the
     note-identified recipient.
